            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Jia Schmidt\u2019s name tells the story of her San Francisco upbringing: the daughter of a precise German-American father who worked as a structural engineer and a graceful mother who immigrated from Shanghai, bringing her love of ink wash painting with her. Raised in the foggy Inner Richmond, Jia\u2019s childhood was a blend of blueprints and rice paper, of structured logic and flowing artistry. This duality defined her.\n\nHer path was supposed to be painting. She enrolled in the Fine Arts program at SF State, losing herself in color theory and large canvases. However, in her second year, a family financial crisis forced her to leave school and find work. A job at a dusty, old-school frame shop in Hayes Valley was meant to be temporary. Instead, it became a calling. She discovered a deep satisfaction in the craft, a perfect marriage of her parents\u2019 worlds. The meticulous math of cutting a mat and the artistry of choosing the right wood grain spoke to her soul.\n\nHer boss, an old Italian framer named Marco, saw her potential and taught her the delicate art of restoration. This was Jia\u2019s turning point. Mending a cracked oil painting or cleaning a century-old photograph felt more meaningful than creating something new. When Marco retired fifteen years ago, Jia used her savings to buy the business.\n\nNow, at 47, Jia is a fixture in her community. Her 2.5-mile bicycle commute from her small Richmond apartment to her Hayes Valley shop is a daily ritual, a constant amid the city's frantic change. Her days are filled with the scent of raw wood and archival glue, her hands steady as she works on pieces for local artists, families preserving heirlooms, and even the occasional gallery.\n\nHer social life is a small, warm circle of fellow small business owners and longtime clients who have become friends. While she has chosen a solitary life, she is never lonely. Jia\u2019s dream isn\u2019t fame or fortune; it\u2019s the quiet hope of one day being entrusted to restore a historically significant piece for a city museum. For now, she finds profound contentment in her work, preserving the small, beautiful histories of San Francisco, one frame at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being eight, kneeling on a chair at the family dining table. On her left, her father\u2019s blueprints, a web of crisp blue lines promising structural order. On her right, her mother\u2019s brush danced across rice paper, a black dragon emerging from a misty gray wash. She felt no conflict, only a quiet harmony. That moment is a compass she still uses, the point where logic and grace first met within her, setting the direction for a life spent finding the beauty in structure and the structure in beauty.\n\n2.\nThe phone call ended, and the door to her painting studio at SF State seemed to seal shut. She was 20. Walking away from campus for the last time, the smell of turpentine felt like a phantom limb. It wasn\u2019t just leaving school; it was the quiet death of the future she\u2019d painted for herself. That sharp sting of helplessness hardened into a core of pragmatism. It was the day she learned that a life\u2019s most important art isn't always on a canvas, but in the crafting of something beautiful from the materials you\u2019re given.\n\n3.\nMarco handed her a tiny, tarnished daguerreotype, the face of a Gold Rush-era woman nearly lost to time. Jia was 23, her hands trembling. Following his patient guidance, she carefully cleaned the glass and stabilized the image. When she finished, the woman\u2019s eyes stared back with startling clarity. A jolt went through her\u2014a feeling more profound than any brushstroke she\u2019d ever made. She wasn\u2019t creating; she was rescuing a story. In that moment, her purpose clicked into place with the satisfying snap of a well-mitered corner.\n\n4.\nThe day Marco retired, he placed the shop\u2019s old brass key in her palm. It was heavy, worn smooth by decades of use. Jia, then 32, felt its weight not just in her hand but in her chest\u2014a terrifying, exhilarating burden of legacy. The scent of sawdust and archival glue suddenly smelled like her own future. This wasn't a job anymore; it was a stewardship. That key locked her into her life\u2019s work, making her a permanent fixture in a city defined by constant, frantic change.\n\n5.\nLast year, a client brought in a smoke-damaged photo, all that was left from a small fire. It showed their grandparents\u2019 Victorian in the Fillmore, before redevelopment erased that world. As Jia painstakingly lifted the soot, revealing the intricate gingerbread trim and the proud faces on the porch, she felt less like a restorer and more like a conduit to a lost San Francisco. It perfectly affirmed her choices: her work wasn't for grand museums, but for the quiet preservation of memory itself."
